Release workflow injects untrusted tag names into PowerShell
Link: https://chatgpt.com/codex/cloud/security/findings/eb020ff413488191966339e9f773549c?sev=critical%2Chigh
Criticality: high (attack path: high)
Status: new

# Metadata
Repo: hatolife/ClipForVRChat
Commit: 6263083
Author: poppo@hato.life
Created: 2026/6/29 13:47:07
Assignee: Unassigned
Signals: Security, Validated, Patch generated, Attack-path

# Summary
Introduced: direct interpolation of the tag ref into PowerShell build and packaging commands creates a CI command-injection vulnerability in the release pipeline.
This commit adds version injection and versioned artifact names by embedding `${{ github.ref_name }}` directly inside PowerShell `run` commands. Git ref names are attacker-controlled input for tag-triggered workflows and can contain shell metacharacters such as quotes, semicolons, `$()`, and `#` while still matching the `v*` tag trigger. For example, a tag name such as `v";whoami;#` would turn the build line into a PowerShell command sequence and execute `whoami` on the runner. The same pattern is present in the `Compress-Archive` destination path. Because this workflow has `contents: write` and publishes release assets, a user who can create a matching tag could execute commands during release, tamper with built artifacts, and publish malicious binaries without changing reviewed source code. The tag value should be validated against an expected release-version pattern such as `^v[0-9]+\.[0-9]+\.[0-9]+$`, passed via environment variables rather than directly interpolated into shell, and separately sanitized before use in file names.

# Validation
## Rubric
- [x] Confirm the release workflow is reachable from attacker-controlled tag names matching `v*` and runs with release-writing permissions.
- [x] Confirm the suspect commit introduced direct `${{ github.ref_name }}` interpolation into PowerShell `run` commands.
- [x] Confirm a malicious tag containing quote/semicolon/comment metacharacters is valid under Git refname rules and matches the workflow trigger.
- [x] Render the vulnerable commands with the malicious tag and show command separation into an attacker-controlled command.
- [ ] Execute the rendered script in real PowerShell/GitHub Actions; not completed because `pwsh` is unavailable in the container, and crash/valgrind/debugger methods are not applicable to this CI injection class.
## Report
Validated the CI command-injection finding against commit 62630835b5b69de1d1a97efa4faefa647494dbef. The release workflow is tag-triggered for `v*` and has `contents: write` at `.github/workflows/release.yml:3-10`. The vulnerable interpolation is present in PowerShell `run` commands at `.github/workflows/release.yml:48-50` and `.github/workflows/release.yml:58-68`: `wails build -ldflags "-X main.version=${{ github.ref_name }}"` and `Compress-Archive ... -DestinationPath "dist/ClipForVRChat-${{ github.ref_name }}-windows-amd64.zip"`. `git show` confirms this commit introduced the interpolation, replacing `wails build` and a static zip name with `${{ github.ref_name }}`. I verified that the example malicious tag `v";whoami;#` is a valid Git tag ref and matches the workflow's `v*` trigger: `git check-ref-format refs/tags/v";whoami;#` returned success, and a temporary repository could create/list that tag. Rendering the workflow commands with that tag produced: `wails build -ldflags "-X main.version=v";whoami;#"` and `Compress-Archive -Path "dist/ClipForVRChat/*" -DestinationPath "dist/ClipForVRChat-v";whoami;#-windows-amd64.zip" -Force`. The PoC splitter shows `whoami` becomes a separate command outside quotes in both cases. `pwsh`, `gdb`, and `valgrind` were not installed in the container; additionally, crash/valgrind/debugger validation is not the appropriate method for a GitHub Actions PowerShell injection. The evidence supports that a user able to create/push a matching tag can execute commands in the privileged release workflow.

# Evidence
github/workflows/release.yml (L3 to 10)
  Note: The release workflow is triggered by pushed tags matching v* and runs with contents: write, so a crafted tag name becomes input to a privileged publishing workflow.

github/workflows/release.yml (L48 to 50)
  Note: The untrusted tag name is interpolated directly into a PowerShell command for ldflags; shell metacharacters in the tag can break out and execute commands.

github/workflows/release.yml (L58 to 68)
  Note: The untrusted tag name is also interpolated into the PowerShell packaging command's destination path, creating a second command-injection point.

